Interaction: Binary

1. Spoofing of the Bank Services External Destination Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Bank Services may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being sent to the attacker's target instead of Bank Services. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:We config trust IPs between Request Processor and Bank Service.

2. External Entity Bank Services Potentially Denies Receiving Data  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Bank Services claims that it did not receive data from a process on the other side of the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:All request sent to Bank Service are logged to central log.

3. Data Flow Binary Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:The communication between Request Processor and Bank Service is in the Intranet.

Interaction: Binary

4. Authenticated Data Flow Compromised  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:An attacker can read or modify data transmitted over an authenticated dataflow.
Justification:Request Processor communicates with SQL Database using TLS.

5. Potential SQL Injection Vulnerability for SQL Database  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:SQL injection is an attack in which malicious code is inserted into strings that are later passed to an instance of SQL Server for parsing and execution. Any procedure that constructs SQL statements should be reviewed for injection vulnerabilities because SQL Server will execute all syntactically valid queries that it receives. Even parameterized data can be manipulated by a skilled and determined attacker.
Justification:Request Processor validate input before pass proper data to the store procedures.

6. Spoofing of Destination Data Store SQL Database  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:SQL Database may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of SQL Database. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:We configure trust IPs between Request Processor and SQL Database.

7. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Request Processor or SQL Database  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Request Processor or SQL Database take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:Consumption under load will be queing instead of sending to Request Processor.

Interaction: Binary

8. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Web Service or Queue  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Queue Processing or Queue take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:We scale out application server farm to reduce number of requests coming to queue.

21. JavaScript Object Notation Processing  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:If a dataflow contains JSON, JSON processing and hijacking threats may be exploited.

22. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Config Service may be able to impersonate the context of Tokenization Service in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:Tokenization Service and Config Service are running in the same server.

23. Collision Attacks  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Attackers who can send a series of packets or messages may be able to overlap data. For example, packet 1 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 0. Packet 2 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 25. Packet 2 will overwrite 75 bytes of packet 1. Ensure you reassemble data before filtering it, and ensure you explicitly handle these sorts of cases.
Justification:Tokenization Service is using &quot;|&quot; operator to concate parameters when hashing.

24. Replay Attacks  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Packets or messages without sequence numbers or timestamps can be captured and replayed in a wide variety of ways. Implement or utilize an existing communication protocol that supports anti-replay techniques (investigate sequence numbers before timers) and strong integrity.
Justification:Config Service and Tokenization Service are running on the same server. So there is no replay attack.

25. Tokenization Service Process Memory Tampered  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:If Tokenization Service is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what Config Service executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then Tokenization Service can tamper with Config Service. Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.
Justification:Tokenization Service only reads data from cache or database then return to Config Service.

Interaction: HTTP
